The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classics lose weight.
Maybe it won't be long.
About the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe, we have written many times on Mobil.cz.
Finally, the Czech Republic confirmed this, which noted that the SMS price is higher for us than for the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to get into a fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and a penetration of over 100 percent.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to say that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this connection, the president of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who said several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It's probably true that the classic operator with his own network probably doesn't have too many chances anymore (otherwise, he'd probably be looking for the frequency already).
But there is one other possibility - a virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has just resulted in a significant reduction in prices, which classical operators had to respond to.
Even before the entry of the stamps such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices on the market in the United Kingdom.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we do not have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and became the fifth largest operator there.
There is a Penta financial group behind Mobilking, which owns U:phone in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they need much less customers than a classical operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile as low-cost operators - offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move and a bet on an unsuspecting target group.
This operator is specifically targeting men.
"The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It's hard to say if a concept like Poland could catch up with us.
Vodafone spokeswoman Miroslav Čepický doubts about this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic without a chance, mobile operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there is any virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations do not look too promising in the Czech Republic.
There is more likely to be a start-up of Mobilking in other countries of our region," she said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It indirectly confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to do so.
Rather, he tries to make sure that no potential competitor does not arise.
For a longer time, the GTS Novera group has not been involved in the launch of a virtual mobile operator, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the business customers field.
"We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only solid but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this option with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have already made progress in the negotiations," said the press spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe he's flashing for better times.
Unofficial information suggests that we should wait for the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
For the time being, however, its origin is accompanied by an impenetrable castle of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far we have not been addressed by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršenj of Telefónika O2 said in his statement.cz
Other operators also appeal to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobilu printer Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2: "We have not yet recorded any viable and mutually advantageous business project on which to build further."
And he goes, "In the T-Mobile network, it's hard for a virtual operator to show up by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table to consider in this short horizon."
Vodafone denies its attention rather to meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepicý says: "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider most beneficial in terms of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The process of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, leading to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
Why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when it comes to operators, they can pull one rope, they also testify to the pull of the U:phone.
Probably the greatest pressure towards the Czech Republic went at the time of the creation of U:phone from T-Mobile.
The publicly available information from the Czech Republic’s website shows this.
But now U:phone fits as an argument why a virtual operator is not allowed.
Martina Kemr said: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player would impose high demands on him and especially on his services."
In view of this approach, however, mobile operators are directly imperceptible to the total lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
It is not just the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately has not been in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries - that it has no power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stand on the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, since the offer of potential candidates was probably not sufficiently interesting for classical operators," said Kristian Chalupa of the ÚHS External Relations Committee in response to our question.
From the representatives of the operators, it is not likely that the comments formulated in this way will surprise them.
It is more than a balanced one from the authority to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "Extra where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
However, pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and price decline are obviously not part of the interests of ÚOHS.
In fact, the whole case is shockingly saddened by the three mobile operators that result from their reactions.
