Hidden among the boisterous amusement parks of Greater Orlando, several miles from everything shiny, loud and round, lies a quiet city in which the pride and complexity of African-American life live.
Eatonville, the first completely black city that was incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "town of five lakes, three croquet playgrounds, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, supply of Quawawawa, two schools and no prison."
Now it's a lonely place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Festival of Zora! to present a gift to Hurston, the most famous female writer of Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a party, even though she made it a tourist stop by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project of the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their real feelings with a white man who "knows us so little that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, when the Montenegrin presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on race, there are many people here who are cautious about the views of strangers.
"We pay great attention to how our story is told," says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of black rise and a community of almost 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is double against the national average.
It is a centre of literature, but also a shaded example of the Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that originated from American slavery.
It is not too surprising that the inhabitants here are both proud and protective.
And the worry about the idea of Eatonville really started when it was Zora, which is the only way that the Hurstons are called.
She introduced her hometown through a heartful book full of murmurs like "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five of the Florida Tourist Guide’s paragraphs changed the city to road number 17, which leads through the often-moved centre of Florida, to the stage of black history and human drama.
With the difference of the big drum in life and in literature, Hurston's reader introduced Joe Clark's first-eatonville mayor into the store, and then she turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown decorated modern national school with well-maintained courts and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can't read or write."
She also mentioned the new husband of the Dash widow and wrote that Lee Glenn "sold drinks of all sorts and anything that fits the hourly hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston Eatonville connected with self-government, but also with illiteracy, re-engagement and sex.
Apparently, this wasn't typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it wasn't a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"The day after, she said it as it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls' choir, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
