"People always liked to see Zora," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair in the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with the rest of the world, had forgotten.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the twentieth century, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived before.
In Eatonville, there were no more mourning rituals or great public readings.
