Interview - Blood That Is Safe Again
Héma-Quebec celebrated yesterday's tenth anniversary and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was justifiably pleased because Héma-Quebec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained confidence in the public, who was seriously shaken after a scandal with contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the state reserve of blood administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusions Committee was contaminated by the Immunity Deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and disfavor, the Canadian Government launched a public investigation in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at explaining the circumstances leading up to such a tragedy and recommending that such a disaster be no longer repeated.
While Judge Krevere went missing with the report, some provinces put in motion a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québek, Gélinea’s committee held this role.
After Gélineau and Krever's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Quebec, which was to operate Québec, and the Canadian blood company to supply all the provinces and both territories.
"When Hema-Quebec started his activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system," Dr. Décary recalls.
"The situation was challenging.
In a systematic effort to increase the safety of blood products and work in this area, we have regained confidence in the public over the following years," he says, adding proudly that at the beginning of 2008, Héma-Quebek had already trusted almost 94 % of the Québek population.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is very fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Quebec has applied the precautionary principle.
"We were then witnessing in Europe the occurrence of many cases of human disease of crazy cows, new variants of disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says a woman who has been leading society since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea whether this disease could spread with blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of Krevera and Gélineau, according to which, if we do not know this and when there is a serious disease at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, a selective measure should be taken.
Thus, in April 1999, we refused blood from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom since 1980 for more than one month.
A few years ago, it was safely proved that this disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the principle of caution made sense."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique appeared on the market to detect HIV virus: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the donor blood to reveal directly the presence of the virus itself, and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests previously used were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when our blood techniques can be detected by the first viruses, explains the specialist.
We've been able to shorten this period for less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing or finding out.
This improvement has made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
The risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV is one person out of 12 million today.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets HIV.
Since Héma-Quebec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products every year, it will take 24 years for the first case of transmission of HIV through the blood product.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe the blood transfusions necessary to heal," says Head of Management Héma-Quebek.
"The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what disease element may appear in the system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by stabbing insects.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to safe supply, Héma-Quebec must also count on sufficient supply.
"The needs are growing because the population is getting old.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for a network of blood donors, which on average consists of only 3% Québecians eligible for donation."
Any healthy person at least 18 years of age who meets the criteria of admissibility, but can only donate blood once in 56 days, that means six times a year.
14% of the people offering blood are not on average accepted because, for example, they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mud colds are found, they are excluded for one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Inadequacies are very rare.
Members of the donor network, however, need to be supplemented proportionally by how old and unable to donate blood.
However, convincing people to give blood is difficult, especially to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life today is so unrestrained that we will only find an hour to donate blood," Francine Décary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Quebec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eye bubbles and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before they are stored in Hema-Quebek, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Québek.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, results in blood rich in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand blood samples from the umbilical cord into the bank, and we assume that we will receive them over a thousand a year.
At the beginning of next year we should start offering them for transplants," Dr. Décary said, which describes the blood collection program from the umbilical cord as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they don't have access to it," because Hema-Quebec doesn't have the resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Québek.
