In particular, it foresees: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the payment of saved public money, new measures to capture the number of homes seized for non-payment and the right to monitor the amount of wages paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
US Finance Minister Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosiová and the representative of the Republicans at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news yesterday, minutes after midnight, after the two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and have reached an agreement that will be effective on the markets," said the representative of Bush's administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and the ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis just taking place on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is a crucial point: if we don't do it, trauma, chaos and disruption of American daily lives will be huge," said Republican Judd Gregg.
During the last hours, negotiations have taken place on the maximum turnout of fear of the effect that further failure should have on the deployment of investors.
The time limit set was the opening of markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US President were invited to the negotiations later, and they both expressed themselves more for the agreement, but they did not mention their dissatisfaction with the fact that it was necessary to resort to such a far-reaching solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attached himself to the agreement on certain measures, in particular measures aimed at enabling the owners of the residence, and measures on remuneration of the heads of the state of employment of the protected companies.
"If we ask the taxpayers to take special measures for the irresponsibleness of some people, there is nothing to be congratulated for.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on television waves.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I would love to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features I've read [showing] that it's something that we're all going to have to spend and what we're going to be able to move on with.
Choosing inactivity is simply unacceptable," he said.
The goal of the 700 billion-dollar plan is to buy off suspicious claims and risk and non-sales assets of American financial institutions for taxpayers' money.
The plan comes after 14 months of the crisis developed by the crackdown on the real estate market, which initially led to the collapse of risk mortgage loans (subprimes), then moved to further, expanded forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of the first draft agreement from last week is a matter of conscience for Republican Members.
From the moment the Democrats came to the conclusion that for some "toxic" assets companies with difficulties the government will only handle, but it will not buy them, there is a belief that the no-east situation is blessed.
In an effort to bring the conflicting views of Congress closer together, a measure has been added that the government will be able to introduce new fees that would help it get its contribution back if, as a result of the programme, it will have to absorb losses for a period of five years.
The new plan is based on a first amount of 250 billion to which another 100 billion can be added, if the President deems it necessary.
The contribution of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shares in saved companies that will pay dividends in case of profit and will be able to resell when it's over.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the borrowing procedures of the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the level of valuation and compensation paid to the managers of the affected companies.
