Truffle Psychology: Why are we spending more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimating goods.
Neurological and economic foundations of this acquaintance - and seemingly irrational - have been able to reveal behavior to researchers in the field of neurology and economics of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in Science magazine, people do not want to be left behind in the eBay auction type, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
Experimental auction research attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers gambled, the other group participated in the auctions, using the FMRI method to examine the active area of the brain of experimental persons.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction game, the important element of which was to switch the other side, began to work intensively in losing the whole brain-skinned, called strioatum.
This brain area plays, in addition to many other functions, a role in the "self-replicating" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, price-cutting can be explained by researchers in an effort to avoid a quick reaction to the striata.
In order to support their theory, the members of the research team carried out a series of economics of financial cross-cutting investigations.
Under different conditions, three groups were auctioned against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product is, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the next group were promised that if they get out of the game, they would get another $15.
The third group received $15, on the contrary, before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members lost the money.
So the difference between the two groups was all about the fact that one was stressed by winning and the other by losing.
However, members of the "against loss" group were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the neurologist's hypothesis.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
They have so far explained the appearances of the observable during auctions of the joys of victory and avoiding the risk.
Until the neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the difference between these two theories by now reaching a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to find a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is reported among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 of them are being treated, and the reason is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, a marked inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the originators of the disease and the diseases they cause differ from one another.
Depending on the underlying diseases, hepatitis type A and E is spread in two main ways: hepatitis type A and E digestive system (e.g. infected with food, water), hepatitis type B, C, D and other blood and body fluid viruses (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Passengers should in any case protect themselves by vaccination against A and B, there is no vaccine-type C virus.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, vomiting.
Then a jaundice, light stool, and dark urine will form on the skin and on the whites of the eyes. Treatment may take two to three weeks.
Each year, millions of people will die worldwide for the more serious type of disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected is treated medically.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected with their disease do not even know, the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells in secret, and so the first symptoms come in many cases up to 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important that timely prevention is carried out on a regular basis.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more often than on average: among people who have had blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C is 200 million.
Since the disease can prove a routine laboratory examination, a person should turn to his practical physician if he notices any sign of unknown origin.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infection and preventing cancer.
September 30th is the world day of hepatitis, which was first organised by organizations representing the sick worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to highlight the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its formation, and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Who believes in God, does it hurt so much?
According to recent research, belief in God works as a certain analgesic that could have made death easier for already Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have done an interesting experiment to explore how belief in the god of pain affects a person, reported the British daily Telegraph.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, they subjected 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists to electric shocks, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to eliminate much of the pain.
The technique of examining the human brain has also shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
Research is the first of a series of studies to be attended by scientists, philosophers and theologians from various parts of the university.
The test was carried out precisely by attaching to the left hand of the test subject a sparking instrument that produced electrical shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to carefully observe two paintings: the 17th century Sasferrat Virgin Mary and the 17th century Lady with the Franciscan Leonardo da Vinci, painted in the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would arouse a certain state of piety among the believers, while da Vinci’s image was chosen because it was not different from the first one and seemed to them a soothing impression.
The test subjects spent half an hour in the MRI scanner and received four of the following 20 electroshocks during this period, while separately monitoring the image with a religious or general theme.
The Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe" as if they were "carefully cared for" and "rested, filled with peace".
They felt 12 percent less pain in watching the picture with religious themes than when they had Leonard’s work ahead.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image and atheists, only the right photograph needs to be found.
"We would have to find a picture that will be very positive, from the position of mother or father," said the psychologist.
England's Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases also change our personality," Wright added.
After such excellent results, it is only a matter of what effect it would have on regulating the pain of the believers if they showed them some Madonna from Leonard or a painter of a similar caliber.
Would it mean looking at the quality of the Virgin Mary achieving even better results?
