An intelligent car imitates the flight of a bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop technologies capable of preventing collisions if not mimicking obstacles in the world of nature?
Like the bees.
The original strategic idea of a surprising project presented at the CEATEC Japan Fair was introduced to engineers from Nissan Beetle. It was about building a new generation of systems that prevent collisions.
In cooperation with the Tokyo University, Nissan designed a biomimetic robot control system BR23C, a robotic minicar equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety cover," explained Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of the brand for Technology PR and Research and Development.
The complex eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see more than 300 degrees in all directions.
In order to copy the complex eye function, engineers were involved in the idea of laser long-range.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 metres ahead of BR23C in the 180-degree field, calculates their distance and sends signals to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into a collision prevention operation.
The obstacle is captured during a fraction of a second, then the robotic car starts to imitate the movements of the bees and turns the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent collisions immediately change direction.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
"If that were not the case, a robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and a robot car project.
They must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety cover, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what bees do to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than the eye blinks.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be upward, downward or upward, it can only be two-dimensional and only in a direction that can be rotated.
In the case of a robot car, instead of endless possibilities offered to bees, only the possibility of rotating movement, speeding up and slowing down was applied.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer accumulators that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means they have longer durability than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, it is an important instinctive, intelligent reaction, not a processing ability, but less data storage.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
It is not necessary to store and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so it constantly uses only a few kilobytes of memory.
He doesn't need a memory with a giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing a technology for immediate avoidance, which is estimated to reach a series of vehicles within ten years.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the specified end-point after the escape.
